{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507314"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:52:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2619"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2619"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.13,0.02,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84177"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3540"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43862"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84177"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to his general practitioner, feeling generally unwell. He reports mild fatigue and decreased appetite over the past three weeks but is otherwise well. He reports longstanding IV drug use and has been sharing needles with his friends. He is unsure whether he has been vaccinated for hepatitis B. He does not take any regular medications and has no significant medical history. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis hepatitis serology shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBsAg: +ve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBs: -ve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIgM anti-HBc: +ve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etotal anti-HBc: +ve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBeAg: +ve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eanti-HBe: -ve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following best describes the patient\u0027s diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute hepatitis B infection","Chronic hepatitis B infection","Resolved hepatitis B infection","Immunity against hepatitis B","Occult hepatitis B infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of hepatitis B is determined through serological testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBsAg (hepatitis B surface antigen) - indicates \u003Cem\u003Eactive infection\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EActive infection\u003C/em\u003E can be \u003Cem\u003Eacute\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003Echronic\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf HBsAg is negative then the infection is resolved\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBs (hepatitis B surface antibody) - indicates \u003Cem\u003Eimmunity gained\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EImmunity\u003C/em\u003E can be gained through \u003Cem\u003Evaccination\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003Eresolved prior infection\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf Anti-HBs is negative then immunity has not been gained\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBc (hepatitis B core antibody) - indicates \u003Cem\u003Estatus of infection\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStatus of infection can be resolved or current\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECurrent infection\u003C/em\u003E can be \u003Cem\u003Eacute\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003Echronic\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntibody can be IgM (\u003Cem\u003Ecurrent acute\u003C/em\u003E) or IgG (past or \u003Cem\u003Ecurrent chronic\u003C/em\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHBeAg refers to a specific e antigen present in some strands of HBV virus. Not all serotypes possess an HBe Ag, therefore it is not routinely tested in an initial HBV serology test. It is often used as a marker for infectivity and used to monitor treatment response\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-HBe refers to antibodies produced against the e antigen. The presence of anti-HBeAg indicates immune control of Hepatitis B, which will help determine whether monitoring or medical treatment is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient tested positive against HBsAg (indicating detectable hepatitis B antigen and an active infectious process). This is supported by the fact that anti-HBc IgM is positive (which is more indicative of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Einfection\u003C/strong\u003E as opposed to a \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic hepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResolved hepatitis B \u003C/strong\u003Einfection indicates clearance of the virus from the body, which is characterised by the absence of HBsAg, and immunity against hepatitis surface and core antigen. Therefore, you would expect -ve HBsAg and anti-HBc IgM, and +ve Anti-HBs and total anti-HBc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccines against hepatitis B\u003C/strong\u003E targets the hepatitis surface antigen. Therefore, in patients immunised against hepatitis B, there would be +ve anti HBs and negative against everything else.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccult hepatitis B \u003C/strong\u003Edescribes a state of infection where the viral DNA is present in the liver (usually accompanied by detectable HBV DNA in the serum). However, the viral capsule cannot be found in the blood, thereby rendering -ve results against hepatitis B surface antigens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Positive HBsAg, along with the presence of core IgM antibodies indicates acute infection with hepatitis B."],"references":["Hepatitis B [Internet]. Hepatitis B - Australian STI Management Guidelines. [cited 2021Jun9]. Available from: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/hepatitis-b#contact-tracing","Hepatitis B | Pathology Tests Explained [Internet]. pathologytestsexplained.org.au. [cited 2024 Feb 2]. Available from: https://pathologytestsexplained.org.au/ptests-pro.php?q=Hepatitis+B","Hepatitis B [Internet]. The Australian Immunisation Handbook. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/hepatitis-b","Saitta, C., Pollicino, T., \u0026 Raimondo, G. (2022). Occult Hepatitis B Virus Infection: An Update. Viruses, 14(7), 1504. https://doi.org/10.3390/v14071504"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2619"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"